\begin_layout Abstract
The temperature variation of the surface tension at a liquid-gas interface
 generates tangential thermocapillary stresses which produce flows in the
 ambient fluid.
 Here, we demonstrate that such active stresses can be produced in a controlled
 manner by inducing a microbubble on a glass substrate that is in contact
 with a liquid in optical tweezers.
 An analytical solution of the thermocapillary problem, based on the Stokes
 and heat equations, yields the flow profile around the bubble.
 The flow around a single bubble causes mesoscopic particles dispersed in
 the ambient liquid to assemble in rings at the bubble interface, which
 we demonstrate experimentally on freely diffusing polystyrene microparticles
 near of the bubble.
 An asymmetric temperature profile generated at the bubble base leads to
 the breaking of azimuthal symmetry in the resultant flow that leads to
 strongly diverging streamlines away from the bubble.
 This is exploited experimentally by inducing simultaneous accumulation
 and pumping of mesoscopic particles that are at different z-planes with
 respect to the bubble.
 The presence of two bubbles in close vicinity causes further modifications
 of the flow field.
 While growing two bubbles on spatially discrete temperature profiles leads
 to a superposition of two separate azimuthally symmetric flows, the same
 problem with two bubbles grown on a temperature gradient leads to even
 stronger breaking of aziumthal symmetry resulting in closed streamlines
 in the axial direction.
 Experimentally, the former leads to the sorting of  mesoscopic particles
 by their assembly on either bubble depending on the initial trajectory
 of the particles with respect to the separatrix in the resultant flow,
 while the latter leads to local vorticity that causes spiraling motion
 in the particles similar to that induced by angular momentum carrying beams
 in optical tweezers.
 Our studies indicate that the active thermocapillary stresses induced by
 multiple microbubbles offer simple routes to complex and controllable micromani
pulation of particles that are typically difficult to achieve in optical
 tweezers.
 
\end_layout

